This project values fast, reliable, maintainable, and explicit tests. Favor the lowest useful level of testing: unit tests first, integration tests when necessary, and very few end-to-end tests.

## Testing strategy

- Respect the test pyramid: many unit tests, some integration tests, very few end-to-end tests.
- Tests must provide fast feedback and stay easy to maintain.
- Always try to test at the lowest meaningful level possible: unit before integration, integration before end-to-end.
- Prefer focused tests over broad, expensive test coverage.
- Choose the test type that gives enough confidence with the lowest maintenance cost.

## Unit tests

- Use unit tests for models, services, helpers, POROs, and domain logic.
- Test one method, class, or business rule in isolation.
- Unit tests should be fast, deterministic, and self-contained.
- Avoid direct ActiveRecord queries in pure unit tests when isolation is the goal.
- Prefer mocks, doubles, `instance_double`, or `build_stubbed` when database persistence is not required.
- Use simple and explicit factories when test data is needed.
- Prefer `described_class` and `subject` when they improve readability.
- Keep examples concise, readable, and clearly named.
- A unit test should run without relying on the database, external APIs, network access, or real background processing whenever possible.

## Integration tests

- Use integration tests for requests, controllers, and real interactions between Rails layers.
- Prefer one clear happy-path integration test per feature to confirm the main flow works end to end inside the app.
- Integration tests should validate real interactions between controllers, services, models, and the database.
- Do not mock internal Rails components such as controllers or models in integration tests.
- Use `get`, `post`, `patch`, `put`, and `delete` to simulate real HTTP requests.
- Always verify the response status and the expected business outcome.
- Mock only true external dependencies such as third-party APIs, webhooks, or external services.
- Keep created test data to the strict minimum needed for the scenario.

## End-to-end system tests

- Use system tests with Capybara to simulate full user journeys.
- Reserve end-to-end tests for truly critical paths such as login, account creation, checkout, or payment.
- Keep system tests to a strict minimum because they are slow and fragile.
- Do not duplicate behavior already well covered by unit or integration tests.
- Use stable and explicit selectors, preferably `data-testid` or other resilient hooks.
- Prefer robust assertions on user-visible behavior over brittle UI implementation details.

## Bug fixing rules

- Before fixing a bug, write a test that fails without the fix and passes with it.
- Write the bug-reproduction test at the lowest useful level possible, usually unit first.
- Briefly document the cause of the bug in the test description or context.
- Keep the regression test focused on the broken behavior being protected.

## General RSpec conventions

- Always use `RSpec.describe` with the appropriate spec type when relevant.
- Spec filenames must follow the `_spec.rb` convention.
- Use `let`, `let!`, and `before` sparingly and avoid unnecessary test magic.
- Prefer clarity and readability over overly clever or overly compact test setup.
- Group examples with explicit `describe` and `context` blocks.
- Use `shared_examples` only for behavior that is genuinely shared and improved by extraction.
- Keep test structure obvious enough that another developer can understand the scenario quickly.

## RSpec example structure

- Do not split one business scenario into many tiny `it` blocks when they all depend on the same setup.
- Each `it` should represent one understandable business scenario.
- Group assertions that belong to the same scenario in the same example.
- Avoid multiplying isolated one-liner examples for scenarios that are really one flow.
- Reserve one-liner `it { ... }` syntax for very simple validations or expectations.

## Factories and mocking practices

- Prefer `FactoryBot.create(:model)` for integration tests where persistence matters.
- Prefer `build_stubbed` or `instance_double` for unit tests when persistence is unnecessary.
- Mock all external APIs, webhooks, mail delivery integrations, and similar external dependencies.
- Never depend on real network access, external files, or real waiting time in tests.
- Factories should be explicit and avoid unnecessary hidden callbacks or surprising defaults.
- Keep factories simple and predictable.
- Use doubles to isolate behavior, not to mirror the full implementation.

## Test maintenance and structure

- Organize specs in the appropriate folders such as `spec/models`, `spec/services`, `spec/requests`, and `spec/system`.
- Tests must be independent from one another.
- Every spec should be runnable in isolation without depending on execution order.
- Remove or refactor obsolete tests when the implementation changes.
- One test should verify one meaningful business behavior.
- Keep the test suite coherent, trustworthy, and easy to evolve over time.

## Expected behavior when generating or editing tests

- Choose the lowest relevant test level that provides enough confidence.
- Do not introduce a system test when a request spec or unit test would be sufficient.
- Prefer tests that are explicit about intent, setup, action, and expected outcome.
- Keep test setup minimal and relevant to the behavior under test.
- When fixing bugs, add the regression test first.
- When refactoring, preserve or improve confidence in behavior without inflating the test suite unnecessarily.
